00:14:39.330 --> 00:14:45.000
For license management,
K2 does complete control at

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:47.770
whatever level you specify
for the software license.

00:14:47.860 --> 00:14:51.660
So you can have unlimited site licenses,
and you can apply that to an application,

00:14:51.660 --> 00:14:54.480
and then everybody that's allowed
to use it will be allowed to use it.

00:14:54.550 --> 00:14:58.100
I can go in and node lock a license
where this specific computer can

00:14:58.100 --> 00:15:01.320
launch this specific application,
and that's the only one

00:15:01.370 --> 00:15:02.920
that's allowed to use it.

00:15:03.460 --> 00:15:06.910
I can also set concurrent licenses
where if I have 50 licenses to

00:15:06.920 --> 00:15:10.760
a computer and I install that
software on 200 different systems,

00:15:10.860 --> 00:15:14.380
only 50 computers will be allowed
to launch that software at a time,

00:15:14.380 --> 00:15:17.040
even though it's installed
on all the computers.

00:15:17.040 --> 00:15:20.520
And plus, you can specify very,
very distinct custom limits

00:15:20.520 --> 00:15:22.180
and restrictions to this.

00:15:22.180 --> 00:15:26.180
And also define multiple profiles
for different sets of computers,

00:15:26.180 --> 00:15:28.870
depending upon how you
want them to be used.

00:15:28.930 --> 00:15:32.570
Being able to reclaim abandoned
licenses would be if you have a

00:15:32.570 --> 00:15:35.960
computer that moves to a different
department and the software isn't

00:15:35.960 --> 00:15:39.090
needed on that computer anymore,
you can see that the license

00:15:39.090 --> 00:15:42.940
isn't in use on there,
and you can actually regain that license

00:15:42.940 --> 00:15:44.520
and apply it to a different system.

00:15:44.520 --> 00:15:48.890
And then plus a full set of
license reporting and analysis.

00:15:48.920 --> 00:15:53.630
Landesk uses a passive agent to
keep track of the software that's

00:15:53.630 --> 00:15:57.550
being launched on a computer,
and to be able to work with the

00:15:57.550 --> 00:16:00.920
inventory scan to go back and say,
what's been run on here?

00:16:00.920 --> 00:16:02.920
So we're managing licenses
through the inventory.

00:16:03.070 --> 00:16:05.040
And then we're managing licenses
through the inventory mechanism,

00:16:05.090 --> 00:16:09.040
and to be also able to track the licenses
and define what people are using,

00:16:09.040 --> 00:16:13.140
depending upon how you want to
set for just an application or

00:16:13.140 --> 00:16:15.040
for the entire application suite.

00:16:15.040 --> 00:16:19.170
To be able to import
specific files for that,

00:16:19.170 --> 00:16:23.090
and to be able to manage license
reconciliation over downgrading

00:16:23.090 --> 00:16:26.040
the rights to a specific
application for somebody,

00:16:26.040 --> 00:16:30.100
and to be able to apply the different
rights policies that you want,

00:16:30.100 --> 00:16:32.040
depending upon what the user
