00:22:11.690 --> 00:22:14.440
instead of gouging you so they can
make their trips out to Hawaii every

00:22:14.440 --> 00:22:16.230
year for the big sales conference.

00:22:17.550 --> 00:22:19.520
That's the sort of data that they want.

00:22:19.530 --> 00:22:21.630
And that's the sort of stuff that,
in my opinion,

00:22:21.660 --> 00:22:24.800
Sassafras K2 does a really good job with.

00:22:24.960 --> 00:22:30.730
Because you can, in a very simple UI,
basically everything happens in one

00:22:30.740 --> 00:22:33.760
unified console where you can see
the number of machines that have

00:22:33.760 --> 00:22:36.990
been called up through the system,
the number of licenses that

00:22:37.060 --> 00:22:41.150
you're tracking and monitoring,
and all the applications that

00:22:41.150 --> 00:22:45.430
have launched at one time
or another on your network.

00:22:45.520 --> 00:22:51.000
And that's the default mode with K2,
where it will, as soon as,

00:22:51.000 --> 00:22:56.540
if you have a K2 client on your machine,
be it Windows, Mac OS, or Linux,

00:22:56.540 --> 00:23:00.940
when a person fires an executable off,
that sends a message back off

00:23:00.950 --> 00:23:04.930
to the main console of K2,
which says, application blah, blah,

00:23:04.930 --> 00:23:06.690
blah has been launched on your network.

00:23:07.080 --> 00:23:10.280
Now, before your end users start
freaking out and saying,

00:23:10.440 --> 00:23:12.420
wait a minute, isn't this spyware?

00:23:12.420 --> 00:23:15.360
Are you monitoring my keystrokes?

00:23:15.360 --> 00:23:18.790
Do you want to know what
downloads I've just made?

00:23:18.800 --> 00:23:22.700
